              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                Determine the range of the function <m>s</m>.
              </p>
            </li>
          </ol>
        </p>
      </li>
      <li xml:id="exer61_integerfunction">
        <p>
          Let <m>f\x \mathbb{Z} \to \mathbb{Z}</m> be defined by <m>f( m ) = 3 - m</m>.
          <ol>
            <li>
              <p>
                Evaluate <m>f( { - 7} ), f( { - 3} ), f( 3 ), \text{ and } f( 7 )</m>.
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                Determine the set of all of the preimages of 5 and the set of all of the preimages of 4.
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                Determine the range of the function <m>f</m>.
              </p>
            </li>
            <li xml:id="exer_sec61-real">
              <p>
                This function can be considered a real function since <m>\Z \subseteq \R</m>.
                Sketch a graph of this function. \note The graph will be an infinite set of points that lie on a line.
                However, it will not be a line since its domain is not <m>\R</m> but is <m>\Z</m>.
              </p>
            </li>
          </ol>
        </p>
      </li>
      <li xml:id="exer_sec61-5">
        <p>
          Let <m>f\x \mathbb{Z} \to \mathbb{Z}</m> be defined by <m>f( m ) = 2m + 1</m>.
          <ol>
            <li>
              <p>
                Evaluate <m>f( { - 7} ), f( { - 3} ), f( 3 ), \text{ and } f( 7 )</m>.
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                Determine the set of all of the preimages of 5 and the set of all of the preimages of 4.
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                Determine the range of the function <m>f</m>.
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                Sketch a graph of the function <m>f</m>.
                See the comments in Exercise<nbsp/><xref ref="exer_sec61-real"/>.
              </p>
            </li>
          </ol>
        </p>
      </li>
      <li xml:id="exer_sec61-9">
        <p>
          Recall that a <em>real function</em>
    <idx><h>real function</h></idx>
    <idx><h>function</h><h>real</h></idx>
          is a function whose domain and codomain are subsets of the real numbers  <m>\R</m>.
          (See <xref ref="realfunction">page</xref>.)
          Most of the functions used in calculus are real functions.
          Quite often,
          a real function is given by a formula or a graph with no specific reference to the domain or the codomain.
          In these cases,
          the usual convention is to assume that the domain of the real function  <m>f</m>  is the set of all real numbers  <m>x</m>  for which  <m>f( x )</m>  is a real number,
          and that the codomain is <m>\mathbb{R}</m>.
          For example, if we define the (real) function  <m>f</m>  by
          <me>
            f( x ) = \frac{x}{{x - 2}}
          </me>,
          we would be assuming that the domain is the set of all real numbers that are not equal to  2 and that the codomain is <m>\R</m>.
          Determine the domain and range of each of the following real functions.
          It might help to use a graphing calculator to plot a graph of the function.
          <ol>
            <li>
              <p>
                The function <m>k</m> defined by <m>k( x ) = \sqrt {x - 3}</m>
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                The function <m>F</m> defined by <m>F( x ) = \ln \left( {2x - 1} \right)</m>
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                The function <m>f</m> defined by <m>f( x ) = 3\sin( {2x} )</m>
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                The function <m>g</m> defined by <m>g( x ) = \dfrac{4}{{x^2 - 4}}</m>
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                The function <m>G</m> defined by <m>G(x) = 4 \cos \left( \pi x \right) + 8</m>
              </p>
            </li>
          </ol>
        </p>
      </li>
      <li xml:id="exer_numberofdivisors">
        <p>
          <em>The number of divisors function</em>.
    <idx><h>number of divisors function</h></idx>
Let <m>d</m> be the function that associates with each natural number the number of its natural number divisors.
          That is, <m>d\x \mathbb{N} \to \mathbb{N}</m> where <m>d( n )</m> is the number of natural number divisors of <m>n</m>.
          For example,
          <m>d( 6 ) = 4</m> since 1, 2, 3, and 6 are the natural number divisors of 6.
          <ol>
            <li>
              <p>
                Calculate <m>d( k )</m> for each natural number <m>k</m> from 1 through 12.
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                Does there exist a natural number <m>n</m> such that <m>d( n ) = 1</m>?
                What is the set of preimages of the natural number 1?
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                Does there exist a natural number <m>n</m> such that <m>d( n ) = 2</m>?
                If so, determine the set of all preimages of the natural number 2.
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                Is the following statement true or false?
                Justify your conclusion.
                For all <m>m, n \in \mathbb{N}</m>,
                if <m>m \ne n</m>, then <m>d( m ) \ne d( n )</m>.
              </p>
            </li>
            <li xml:id="exer_numberofdivisorse">
              <p>
                Calculate <m>d\!\left( {2^k } \right)</m> for <m>k = 0</m> and for each natural number <m>k</m> from 1 through 6.
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                Based on your work in Exercise<nbsp/><xref ref="exer_numberofdivisorse"/>,
                make a conjecture for a formula for
                <m>d\!\left( {2^n } \right)</m> where <m>n</m> is a nonnegative integer.
                Then explain why your conjecture is correct.
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                Is the following statement is true or false?
                <ul>
                  \item For each <m>n \in \mathbb{N}</m>, there exists a natural number <m>m</m> such that <m>d( m ) = n</m>.
                </ul>
              </p>
            </li>
          </ol>
        </p>
      </li>
      <li xml:id="exer_sec62-5">
        <p>
          In Exercise<nbsp/><xref ref="exer_numberofdivisors"/>,
          we introduced the <em>number of divisors function</em>
    <idx><h>number of divisors function</h></idx> <m>d</m>.
          For this function, <m>d\x \mathbb{N} \to \mathbb{N}</m>,
          where <m>d( n )</m> is the number of natural number divisors of <m>n</m>.
          A function that is related to this function is the so-called
          <em>set of divisors function</em>.
    <idx><h>set of divisors function</h></idx>
This can be defined as a function <m>S</m> that associates with each natural number the set of its distinct natural number factors.
          For example,
          <m>S( 6 ) = \left\{ {1, 2, 3, 6} \right\}</m> and <m>S(10) = \{1, 2, 5, 10 \}</m>.
          <ol>
            <li>
              <p>
                Discuss the function <m>S</m> by carefully stating its domain,
                codomain,
                and its rule for determining outputs.
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                Determine <m>S( n )</m> for at least five different values of <m>n</m>.
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                Determine <m>S( n )</m> for at least three different prime number values of <m>n</m>.
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                Does there exist a natural number <m>n</m> such that <m>\card (S(n)) = 1</m>?
                Explain. [Recall that <m>\card (S(n))</m> is the number of elements in the set <m>S( n )</m>.]
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                Does there exist a natural number <m>n</m> such that <m>\card (S(n)) = 2</m>?
                Explain.
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                Write the output for the function <m>d</m> in terms of the output for the function <m>S</m>.
                That is, write <m>d( n )</m> in terms of <m>S( n )</m>.
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                Is the following statement true or false?
                Justify your conclusion.
                <ul>
                  \item For all natural numbers <m>m</m> and <m>n</m>, if <m>m \ne n</m>, then <m>S ( m ) \ne S ( n )</m>.
                </ul>
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                Is the following statement true or false?
                Justify your conclusion.
                <ul>
                  \item For all sets <m>T</m> that are subsets of <m>\mathbb{N}</m>, there exists a natural number <m>n</m> such that <m>S( n ) = T</m>.
                </ul>
              </p>
            </li>
          </ol>
        </p>
      </li>
    </ol>
